title: For Sale:  German Sport Guns GSG-522 SD, .22 LR
postcontent:
This is a like new (in original box) German Sport Guns GSG-522 SD, .22 LR.  Item G-39479-2


GSG 522

The German Sport Guns GSG 522 is a great replica of the famous Heckler & Koch MP5. The MP5 has been around for a long time and still looks modern….it started in 1966! The MP5 has been used in SWAT teams in the USA and special military forces all over the world and come in all kinds of variations and caliber sizes.  They’ve also been in lots of movies because it’s one of the coolest looking sub machine guns ever created.

Sure everyone would love to own one and shoot one…however HK stopped making the civilian versions of the MP5 in the 1980′s which means to get a real HK select-fire 9mm MP5 will cost around $15,000-25,000. You also have to get some paper work filled with the ATF since it’s full auto. Even the quality replicas are over $1,500 – $2,500 (learn more about the original MP5).  Not to mention shooting 9mm rapid fire with a 25 round clip would get expensive fast. Each magazine you shoot would cost you at least $6-$8…shooting three magazines at the range would set you back at least $20.

Back in 2008 GSG started selling the 552 in a few different versions and it has been a very popular .22. There are the 522, 522 SD, and the MP5K and slight variations of each with different stocks, barrel lengths and accessories.

There is the 522 Carbine RS above with what looks like a sweet suppressor screwed on the end… unfortunately the sweet looking suppressor is fake due to a lot of reasons that include cost and regulations.

We have additional higher resolution pictures of this item available upon request.

Call or come by Green Country Arms & Pawn in Tulsa, OK, (9075 E 31st St, Tulsa, OK). Be sure to mention that you saw our ad on Armslist.

title: For Trade:  Taurus PT22 .22 pistol. Great Condition. FOR TRADE
postcontent:
Taurus PT-22 semi-auto pistol in great condition. Gun works perfectly with zero issues. Very accurate and has been a great pocket gun. Gun small enough that a person's hand covers the entire firearm, very discreet. Less than 200 rounds through it. One interesting point about these guns is that you don’t have to pull the slide back to chamber the weapon, there is an additional option. If you are elderly or disabled, or suffer from an ailment that prevents you from pulling a slide back on a handgun, this gives you an option that will work.
To load the gun (the optional way), push forward on the barrel catch lever, and the back of the barrel will tip up, exposing an empty chamber. Place a round directly into the breach and snap the barrel down, the gun is now loaded. Then it fires and cycles like any other semi-auto.  Or, of course, you can load the gun the traditional way...simply feed a round from the magazine by pulling back the slide and letting go.  Either way, the magazine holds 8 rounds, plus one in the chamber. This is double action, it has no hammer to cock, so you chamber a round, pull trigger and it fires. It does have a safety. The design of the firearm would make it nearly impossible for an accidental discharge in a pocket or purse.  I wish to trade only. Always looking for the next new gun. Will consider anything really, but long guns and handguns are generally what I am looking for.

title: For Sale:  HACT Trigger
location: North Raleigh, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
I have for sale, a used, fully functional HACT trigger off of a Howa 1500 .308 Heavy barreled rifle. Has 3-postion safety. Has some camo paint on the safety lever as well. But Nothing that affects the functioning of it.

I am pretty sure this will fit any newer Howa rifles, maybe even the older ones that came out before they started selling them with these HACT triggers. Trigger pull is about 3 lbs. I loved this trigger, but decided to get a Timney which had lower adjustable pull weight. One thing I definitely liked more about this trigger then the Timney, is it's a 2 stage as opposed to a single. The Timney has a very clean single stage break, but I wish it had the 2 stage pull that the HACT has. Just my preference in a long range rifle platform. 

This is a great trigger assembly, I just don't need it. New they run around $100.
I am asking $40
